Review Comments: This manuscript provides a timely and well-motivated survey of GPU acceleration in computational lithography. 
The topic is highly relevant to both the academic and industrial communities, and the authors succeed in framing computational lithography 
from a system-level perspective rather than as isolated kernel optimizations. The proposed taxonomy and the emphasis on end-to-end GPU residency 
are particularly valuable. However, in its current form, the manuscript requires substantial revision to meet the standards of a high-impact review article. 

My main comments are as follows.
Key performance and memory claims should be accompanied by clear descriptions of baselines, problem scales, precision settings, and 
whether results reflect end-to-end workflows or isolated kernels.

Placeholder-style references and indirect attributions should be replaced with explicit, traceable citations, and the literature review should focus more on 
synthesis and comparison rather than sequential description.

More concrete guidance on precision choices, determinism, and their impact on lithography metrics would significantly enhance the practical value of the review.

A more balanced discussion of portability, alternative GPU ecosystems, and the implications of vendor dependence would strengthen the neutrality of the survey.

An overview schematic summarizing the taxonomy, computational workflow, and GPU acceleration strategies would greatly improve clarity and help readers grasp the 
overall structure of the review more efficiently.


Typographical errors, inconsistent terminology, and occasional abrupt transitions should be corrected to improve readability and professionalism.
